Diagnosis and reatment
he differential diagnosis of sudden cardiac death includes the following: hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, coronary artery abnormalities, arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia, long  syndrome, rugada syndrome, olf-arkinson-hite syndrome, dilated cardiomyopathy, arfan syndrome, aortic valve stenosis, mitral valve prolapse, coronary artery disease, myocarditis, asthma, heat stroke, drug abuse, and a ruptured cerebral artery. hese conditions and injuries must be ruled out before a definitive diagnosis of  can be made. owever, a history of witnessed trauma to the chest should immediately raise suspicion of . mmediate initiation of cardiopulmonary resuscitation and automated external defibrillator () protocol is paramount during a witnessed  event.
cute reatment and the ole of arly defibrillation is critical for survival of . nfortunately, resuscitation after  is often unsuccessful.14,21,22 n a ink et al swine model, animals that were defibrillated in less than 2 minutes generally survived, whereas among those that were defibrillated in more than 4 minutes, fewer than half survived.9  use in animals within 1 to 2 minutes resulted in 100% and 92% success, respectively. nly 46% of shocks were successful after 4 minutes; after 6 minutes, success rates dropped to 25% ( < .0001).9 n human cases, resuscitation within 3 minutes resulted in a survival rate of 25% (17 of 68 cases); when resuscitation was prolonged beyond 3 minutes, the survival rate dropped to 3% (1 of 38 cases).7,21 he total survival rate from  is approximately 15%,7,21 which has improved from 10% in 2001.13Diagnosis and Treatment
The differential diagnosis of sudden cardiac death includes the following: hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, coronary artery abnormalities, arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia, long QT syndrome, Brugada syndrome, Wolf-Parkinson-White syndrome, dilated cardiomyopathy, Marfan syndrome, aortic valve stenosis, mitral valve prolapse, coronary artery disease, myocarditis, asthma, heat stroke, drug abuse, and a ruptured cerebral artery. These conditions and injuries must be ruled out before a definitive diagnosis of CC can be made. However, a history of witnessed trauma to the chest should immediately raise suspicion of CC. Immediate initiation of cardiopulmonary resuscitation and automated external defibrillator (AED) protocol is paramount during a witnessed CC event.
Acute Treatment and the Role of AEDEarly defibrillation is critical for survival of CC. Unfortunately, resuscitation after CC is often unsuccessful.14,21,22 In a Link et al swine model, animals that were defibrillated in less than 2 minutes generally survived, whereas among those that were defibrillated in more than 4 minutes, fewer than half survived.9 AED use in animals within 1 to 2 minutes resulted in 100% and 92% success, respectively. Only 46% of shocks were successful after 4 minutes; after 6 minutes, success rates dropped to 25% (P < .0001).9 In human cases, resuscitation within 3 minutes resulted in a survival rate of 25% (17 of 68 cases); when resuscitation was prolonged beyond 3 minutes, the survival rate dropped to 3% (1 of 38 cases).7,21 The total survival rate from CC is approximately 15%,7,21 which has improved from 10% in 2001.13
